uthorization2star  aRecent literature has identified modern “parenting” as an expert-led practice—one which begins with pre-pregnancy decisions, entails distinct types of intimate relationships, places intense burdens on mothers and increasingly on fathers too. Exploring within diverse historical and global contexts how men and women make—and break—relations between generations when becoming parents, this volume brings together innovative qualitative research by anthropologists, historians, and sociologists. The chapters focus tightly on inter-generational transmission and demonstrate its importance for understanding how people become parents and rear children.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aFamilies. 0aIntergenerational relations. 0aParenthood. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  achild-rearing.  agenerations.  ahabituation.  aintergenerational transmission.  amemory.  aparenthood.  areproduction.1 aBreengaard, Michala Hvidt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChowbey, Punita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Shane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeron, Adom Philogene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHertog, Ekaterina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPooley, Siân, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPooley, Siân, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPralat, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQureshi, Kaveri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQureshi, Kaveri, eeditor.4edt4http